The '''little cuckoo-dove''' ('''''Macropygia ruficeps''''') is a [[species]] of [[bird]] in the family [[Columbidae]]. It is a reddish brown pigeon, and is found in Brunei, China, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, Thailand, and Vietnam.<ref name="iucn status 11 November 2021" /> It is listed as a species of&nbsp;[[least concern]]&nbsp;on the&nbsp;[[IUCN Red List of Endangered Species|International Union for Conservation of Nature Red List&nbsp;of Endangered Species]].

== Description ==
The little cuckoo-dove is a reddish brown pigeon, measuring {{Convert|27|to|30|cm|abbr=on}} in length, and weighing {{Convert|74|to|88|g|abbr=on}}.<ref name="hbw2">{{cite web|url=http://www.hbw.com/species/little-cuckoo-dove-macropygia-ruficeps|title=Little Cuckoo-dove (''Macropygia ruficeps'')|last1=Baptista|first1=L.F.|last2=Trail|first2=P.W.|year=2017|editor1-last=del Hoyo|editor1-first=Josep|editor2-last=Elliott|editor2-first=Andrew|work=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive|publisher=Lynx Edicions|access-date=2017-09-21|url-access=subscription |last3=Horblit|first3=H.M.|last4=Boesman|first4=P.|editor3-last=Sargatal|editor3-first=Jordi|editor4-last=Christie|editor4-first=David A|editor5-last=de Juana|editor5-first=Eduardo}}</ref> It has cinnamon buff [[plumage]].&nbsp;It has greyish white [[Iris (anatomy)|irides]]. The [[beak]] is brown, and has a black tip. The feet are coral red in colour.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZaXi-P-heDQC&pg=PA133|title=A Field Guide to the Birds of China|last1=MacKinnon|first1=John Ramsay|last2=MacKinnon|first2=John|last3=Phillipps|first3=Karen|last4=He|first4=Fen-qi|date=2000|publisher=Oxford University Press Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-854940-6|pages=133|language=en}}</ref> The tail is long, and it differentiates the little cuckoo-dove from other [[Sympatry|sympatric]] (species existing in the same geographic area and thus frequently encountering one another) pigeons.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JMGkAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA274|title=Pigeons and Doves: A Guide to the Pigeons and Doves of the World|last=Gibbs|first=David|date=2010|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-4081-3555-6|pages=274–275|language=en}}</ref> Little cuckoo-doves travel in loose flocks.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Morris |first=Pat |date=July 2013 |title=A Field Guide to the Birds of Peninsular Malaysia and Singapore (Second Edition) by Allen Jeyarajasingam & Alan Pearson. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2012. ISBN 978-0-19-963943-4. Paperback. £34.95. |journal=Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society |volume=168 |issue=3 |page=669 |doi=10.1111/zoj.12028 |issn=0024-4082|doi-access=free }}</ref>

== Distribution and habitat ==
The little cuckoo-dove is found in evergreen hill forests and forest peripheries, in the north of its range. Southwards, it is&nbsp;found in drier forests and in adjacent areas of [[Secondary forest|second-growth forests]]. It is also found in cultivated areas. It is commonly found in submontane habitats&nbsp;at elevations of {{Convert|300|to|2000|m|abbr=on}} above sea level. It has also been recorded at heights of at least {{Convert|3000|m|}} from sea level on [[Mount Kinabalu|Mount Kinabulu]], and sometimes at sea level.<ref name=":0" />

== Status and conservation ==
Since 1998, the little cuckoo-dove has been rated as a species of&nbsp;[[least concern]]&nbsp;on the&nbsp;[[IUCN Red List&nbsp;of Endangered Species]]. This is because it has a large range—more than 20,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>&nbsp;(7,700&nbsp;mi<sup>2</sup>)—and because it has a stable population trend. Also, although its population numbers have not been determined, they are thought to be above 10,000, which is above the criterion to warrant a&nbsp;[[Vulnerable species|vulnerable]]&nbsp;rating. It is described to be common in the southern part of its range, and uncommon in the northern part of its range. It is thought to have no major threats.<ref name="iucn status 11 November 2021" />

